Here's a complete example. I'll use a weather API as a concrete REST wrapper.

### Tool Class â€” `WeatherTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    private const string BaseUrl = "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1";

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get current weather for a location by latitude and longitude.")]
    public async Task<string> GetCurrentWeather(
        [Description("Latitude of the location (e.g. 47.6)")] double latitude,
        [Description("Longitude of the location (e.g. -122.3)")] double longitude,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching weather for ({Lat}, {Lon})", latitude, longitude);

        var url = $"{BaseUrl}/forecast?latitude={latitude}&longitude={longitude}"
                + "&current=temperature_2m,wind_speed_10m,relative_humidity_2m";

        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Look up geographic coordinates for a city name.")]
    public async Task<string> GeolocateCity(
        [Description("City name to search for (e.g. 'Seattle')")] string cityName,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var url = $"https://geocoding-api.open-meteo.com/v1/search?name={Uri.EscapeDataString(cityName)}&count=3";
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }
}
```

### `Program.cs` â€” stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: route all logging to stderr so stdout stays clean for JSON-RPC
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient();  // registers IHttpClientFactory + HttpClient

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();      // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|-------|-----------|---------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in the constructor â€” shared across all tool methods |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | Services as method params â€” resolved per call |

**Key rules:**

1. **DI parameters are invisible to the LLM.** The SDK distinguishes between "tool input" params (those with `[Description]`) and "injected" params (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<>`, and any DI-registered service). Only described params appear in the JSON schema sent to clients.

2. **Registration happens in `Program.cs`.** Call `builder.Services.AddHttpClient()` (or `.AddSingleton<IMyService, MyService>()`, etc.) so the container can resolve them.

3. **Non-static classes** (like the example above) are instantiated by the DI container, so constructor injection with primary constructors works naturally.

4. For **static classes**, put DI services directly in the method signature:
   ```csharp
   [McpServerToolType]
   public static class Tools
   {
       [McpServerTool, Description("Ping a URL")]
       public static async Task<string> Ping(
           [Description("URL to ping")] string url,
           HttpClient httpClient,              // injected, not in schema
           CancellationToken cancellationToken) // injected
       {
           var resp = await httpClient.GetAsync(url, cancellationToken);
           return $"Status: {(int)resp.StatusCode}";
       }
   }
   ```

To scaffold this project quickly:
```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n WeatherMcpServer
```
Then replace the generated tool class and `Program.cs` with the code above.
